companion_advice: Pressure doesn’t always sound loud. Sometimes it hides in guilt or silence. But you’re allowed to pause, say no, or change your mind—at any time. That’s real safety.

companion_advice: A good listener doesn’t just hear your words—they make space for your feelings. You don’t need someone who’s perfect. You need someone who stays kind when it matters.

question_text:
Ghosting doesn’t mean you’re unworthy—it means they didn’t know how to show up.
You don’t have to carry their silence like it’s your fault.

If someone ghosted you, what would you tell yourself?
option_text: A. Maybe they’re just busy. I don’t want to jump to the worst story.
response_message: A.That’s a calm and generous way to think. You’re giving them space without jumping to hurtful conclusions. That takes maturity.
companion_advice:
Ghosting often says more about them than you. If you’re left in the dark, don’t light it with self-blame. You deserve clarity, not confusion.
1. Light & low-pressure
"Hey! Just wanted to say hi—hope everything’s okay on your end."
2. Honest but kind
"I noticed we haven’t talked in a bit. If you’ve been busy, no worries—I just wanted to check in."
3. Casual + gives an out
"Not sure if your week’s been wild or if I misread things—but either way, wishing you well :)"
4. Honest + invites closure
"If you’re not feeling this anymore, I totally get it. Just wanted to close the loop instead of wondering."

question_text: If someone ghosted you, what would you tell yourself?
option_text: B. It’s probably my fault. I must’ve said something weird.
response_message: B. It’s normal to replay the conversation in your head and wonder if you messed up. You care—and that’s part of being human.
companion_advice:
But ghosting usually says more about the other person’s communication skills than your worth. If someone disappears without a word, that’s on them—not on you. The right people won’t leave you guessing like this.
But if you want closure or clarity, here’s a gentle message you can send:
"Hey, I’ve been wondering if I said something off. If so, I’d want to know—not to pressure you, just to learn. But if you’re done, that’s okay too."
Or a shorter version:
"If I said something that felt off, I’m open to hearing it. No pressure to reply—just wanted to say that."
But you don’t need to say anything unless it will bring peace.
Silence can be the loudest message—and you’re allowed to walk away too.

question_text: If someone ghosted you, what would you tell yourself?
option_text: C. Their loss. I deserve better than vanishing acts.
response_message: C. That’s a strong, self-respecting stance. You know your value, and you’re not begging for crumbs. That’s powerful.
companion_advice:
You already know your worth—now protect your peace.

Inspired by Jefferson Fisher, a lawyer who teaches calm communication:

1. Don’t chase.
2. Say (in your own words): “This silence isn’t working for me, so I’m stepping back.”
3. Then go enjoy your life..

You don’t need their reply to move forward.

question_text: If someone ghosted you, what would you tell yourself?
option_text: Other

What hurts most after a breakup?
option_text: A. Not knowing if they ever meant it at all.
response_message: A. You keep reaching for meaning, but it slips through. It’s not just the end that hurts—it’s the fear that you never really mattered.
companion_advice: Some people leave without giving answers—but their silence doesn’t erase what you gave. Even if they moved on fast, that doesn’t mean it was nothing. You were there. Fully. That says something about who you are—and that matters.

question_text: What hurts most after a breakup?
option_text: B. One day we were everything. Now we’re strangers.
response_message: B. You lost more than a person. You lost comfort, rhythm, inside jokes. And now there’s this strange quiet where they used to be.
companion_advice: Let the space be what it is for now. You’re not empty—you’re adjusting. That’s what healing looks like at first.

question_text: What hurts most after a breakup?
option_text:

Feels like I was the only one hit.
response_message: C. It stings when they move on like it was just a bump. You’re stuck in the ache, and they’re posting brunch pics like it never happened.
companion_advice: Their surface doesn’t tell their whole story—and even if it did, this isn’t a race. You’re healing, not performing. Stay with your own timeline. You’re not behind. You’re just in your own story—and that story matters.

companion_advice: Power’s complicated. Try asking: “If this were me—what would I hope someone else would do?” Even small actions matter. Get an adult to help if you can't.

question_text: You see someone being physically bullied in the hallway—like shoved, blocked, or grabbed. What do you do?

companion_advice: If you wish you had done something, hold onto that. Next time, even shouting for help is action. Get an adult to help if you can't.

companion_advice: You don’t have to solve everything yourself. Knowing when to bring in backup is real strength.

question_text:
No judgment—everyone handles tension their own way. Some pause. Some pounce. Some panic and joke.
What’s your go-to rhythm? 
We’re not clocking you like it’s the Olympics—just curious what your survival setting is.
How many seconds do you pause before replying—especially with difficult people?
option_text: A. I pause forever because I’m scared to say the wrong thing.
response_message: A. You need time to think—and that’s not weakness, it’s wisdom.
companion_advice: If you pause for too long, that’s emotional radar. Try asking yourself, 'What am I avoiding?'

question_text: How many seconds do you pause before replying—especially with difficult people?
option_text: B. I reply right away with filler words until I figure out what I mean.
response_message: B. You rush to be polite. But rushing steals your voice sometimes.
companion_advice: Instant reactions feel powerful, but try waiting one breath next time. It changes everything.

question_text: How many seconds do you pause before replying—especially with difficult people?
option_text: C. Depends how fast a joke pops into my head.  Sometimes half a second.  Sometimes never.
response_message: C. Half a second is plenty—when you’ve got punchlines ready.
companion_advice: Try timing yourself in convos this week. Count the seconds before speaking. What do you notice?

question_text: How many seconds do you pause before replying—especially with difficult people?
option_text: D. I wait 3 seconds and then respond.
response_message: D. You want to say the right thing for both of you. That 3 seconds are golden.
companion_advice: Your pause is already powerful—now use it to listen deeper, not just calm yourself. You’ll hear what’s really going on.

question_text: How many seconds do you pause before replying—especially with difficult people?
option_text: E. No pause.  If I don’t like them, I say it straight.
response_message: E. You say it straight, but sometimes softness has power too.
companion_advice: If you say it straight, own it. But also track: when does speaking fast help, and when does it cost you peace?

Some bonds are loud. Some are quiet. All of them shape you.

What’s the dynamic you know too well?
option_text: A. I try to stay out of their way.
response_message: A. You try to stay out of sibling chaos. That’s self-protection—and you’re allowed to take up space too.
companion_advice: If you feel invisible, try taking up a little more space—ask for something small, out loud. It’s okay to exist loudly sometimes.

question_text: What’s your sibling energy?
option_text: B. We’re solid—even if we don’t need to say it much.
response_message: B. Your bond doesn’t need big words—it’s built on time, trust, and quiet knowing.
companion_advice: Even if you don’t say it much, it still matters. Try sending them one message—just something like: ‘You’re cool.’ It might mean more than you think.

question_text: What’s your sibling energy?
option_text: C. If they touch my stuff, I declare war.
response_message: C. You draw the line when your space is crossed. That’s not drama—it’s boundaries.
companion_advice: Feeling invaded makes sense—but power isn’t just about reacting. Try this instead: set a clear line before the next battle. A calm “Please don’t touch my stuff—just ask” can be surprisingly powerful.

question_text: What’s your sibling energy?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Every family has tension—loud or quiet, it shows up. Some people rush in. Some shut down. Some disappear. There’s no perfect way to handle it—but your pattern comes from somewhere—and it matters.

When someone in your family is upset, what do you do?
option_text: A. Stay quiet and try not to make it worse.
response_message: A. You keep your distance to stay safe. That’s not cold—it’s cautious.
companion_advice: Silence keeps the peace—but it can also leave you feeling invisible. Try this: ‘I see you’re upset. I’m here if you need.’ That’s calm and present.

question_text: When someone in your family is upset, what do you do?
option_text: B. Ask what’s wrong and try to help if I can.
response_message: B. You show up with care. That’s a gift, even if they take it for granted.
companion_advice: Helping is a strength—but it’s okay to ask: ‘Is this something I can help with—or just something you need to vent?’ Boundaries are part of care too.

question_text: When someone in your family is upset, what do you do?
option_text: C. I get frustrated—it’s not my job to fix everything.
response_message: C. You’re tired of fixing everything. That frustration is real—and it matters.
companion_advice: You don’t have to be the emotional janitor. Next time, try this: ‘I care, but I also need space right now.’ That’s not selfish—it’s honest.

question_text: When someone in your family is upset, what do you do?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Every house argues—it’s part of being human. But how it starts… and how it ends… tells you a lot. What’s the script you know by heart?

How do arguments usually go in your house?
option_text: A. I shut down and disappear till it’s over.
response_message: A. You shut down because it feels safer than speaking up. You’re not weak—you’re surviving.
companion_advice: If people yell over each other, try becoming the pause. Say, ‘Can we slow down for a second?’ You’d be surprised how powerful that is.

question_text: How do arguments usually go in your house?
option_text: B. We eventually talk things out peacefully—even if it’s messy.
response_message: B. Even messy conversations can lead to growth. You’re showing real maturity.
companion_advice: If talking things out works eventually, ask: What helps? Next time, start there.

question_text: How do arguments usually go in your house?
option_text: C. I yell. They yell. It never ends well.
response_message: C. If yelling is the pattern, pause is the first repair. You don’t have to fix everything—but you can stop the spiral.
companion_advice: If arguments get personal, name your boundary: ‘I’m not okay with being talked to like that.’ You don’t have to accept disrespect to stay in the room.

question_text: How do arguments usually go in your house?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Most tension starts small—until it builds into something big. It’s not just what people fight about—it’s what goes unsaid that builds pressure.

What sparks it most where you live?
option_text: A. Little things that pile up until someone snaps.
response_message: A. Tiny things build into explosions. That doesn’t mean you’re dramatic—it means no one’s naming the small stuff.
companion_advice: When small things aren’t talked about, they grow sharp. Try naming one thing before it piles up— in a calm moment. That’s how pressure releases safely.

question_text: What sparks it most where you live?
option_text: B. Different opinions—but we work through it.
response_message: B. You disagree, and you talk it out. That’s not tension—it’s growth.
companion_advice: That’s emotional teamwork. If something works, notice what it is: timing, tone, words. Use that pattern next time things get tense.

question_text: What sparks it most where you live?
option_text: C. Bad moods bouncing around like dodgeballs.
response_message: C. Mood swings rule the day. You’ve learned to dodge emotional dodgeballs.
companion_advice: You’re dodging emotion to stay safe—and that makes sense. But hiding isn’t the only option. Next time the mood gets heavy, try saying: “Can we all take a deep breath?” It’s a small ask, but it can shift the whole room—and remind you that your calm has power too.

question_text: What sparks it most where you live?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Every couple fights—it’s part of being close. But how they argue teaches you something: What respect looks like. Whether people take responsibility.
Whether things get repaired—or just buried.

How do your parents argue?
option_text: A. They yell or fight loudly
response_message: A. Even walls know too much.
companion_advice:
Try creating a post-argument ritual for yourself: music, a walk, texting someone - a calm space, even when the house isn’t.
When it feels safe, you could try saying: “It means a lot to me when you and [Mom/Dad] get along. I feel better when things are peaceful between you.”
You’re not trying to control anything. Just showing what matters to you.

question_text: How do your parents argue?
option_text: B. Cold silence for days
response_message: B. The quiet is sometimes louder than shouting.
companion_advice:
Long silences can feel heavy.
And if it feels okay, try something small like: “Things feel kind of tense. Are you alright?”
It’s gentle, and it might soften the silence.

question_text: How do your parents argue?
option_text: C. They talk it out calmly
response_message: C. Disagreements don’t have to be destruction.
companion_advice: That’s powerful to witness. Try asking them how they learned to do that—seriously. Their answer might teach you something surprising.

question_text: How do your parents argue?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Even when it’s hard to watch, arguments can teach us things. 

What have your parents’ arguments taught you—about love, respect, or yourself?
option_text: A. That real love doesn’t always look calm—but it should still feel safe.

question_text: What have your parents’ arguments taught you—about love, respect, or yourself?
option_text: B. That I want to grow differently from their patterns.

question_text: What have your parents’ arguments taught you—about love, respect, or yourself?
option_text: C. That sometimes arguing is better than pretending.

question_text: What have your parents’ arguments taught you—about love, respect, or yourself?
option_text: D. I’m not sure yet—but I’ve been paying attention.

question_text: What have your parents’ arguments taught you—about love, respect, or yourself?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Every household has repeat fights—like a playlist stuck on loop.

What do your parents usually argue about?
option_text: A. Money
response_message: A. Bills speak louder than love sometimes.
companion_advice:
Money stress is heavy—and it often shows up as fear or pressure. 
Feeling this pressure is hard—but it can also show you what matters to you. You may not be able to change things now, but the strength you’re building could shape what you do later—for yourself and for them.

question_text: What do your parents usually argue about?
option_text: B. Housework
response_message: B. Dirty dishes, clean fights.
companion_advice: Chores can carry more weight than they seem. If the tension spills over, try offering help without fixing the fight. Even one small act can lower the temperature.

question_text: What do your parents usually argue about?
option_text: C. Loyalty or trust
response_message: C. Shaky trust shakes the whole house.
companion_advice:
When trust breaks between your parents, it can feel like nothing is steady anymore—even if no one talks about it.
Remember: what’s between them isn’t yours to fix. But your feelings are real. Try grounding yourself in something that doesn’t change—music, movement, writing, or talking to someone you trust. You deserve a space that feels solid, even if the house doesn’t.

question_text: What do your parents usually argue about?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Parents don’t always say what’s really going on. But you feel it—through their moods, their tone, their silence.

What do you think is weighing on them lately?
option_text: A. Worrying about money and job security
response_message: A. You see the tension—even when they try to hide it.
companion_advice:
Money stress is heavy—and it often shows up as fear or pressure. 
Feeling this pressure is hard—but it can also show you what matters to you. You may not be able to change things now, but the strength you’re building could shape what you do later—for yourself and for them.

question_text: What do you think is weighing on them lately?
option_text: B. Worrying about health—their own or the family’s
response_message: B. You can feel fear even when it’s not spoken out loud.
companion_advice: Health fears echo through the house sometimes. Try creating little safety rituals for yourself—like music, journaling, walks—to remind yourself you still have calm inside you.

question_text: What do you think is weighing on them lately?
option_text: C. They worry about my future—but I mostly just feel pressure.
response_message: C. Their hopes for you sometimes sound like pressure—but underneath is love.
companion_advice:
Their worries aren’t about you failing—they’re about not knowing how to help. If it feels okay, try saying:
“I know you care about where I end up. I care too. I’d just love to feel a little more trust while I figure it out.”
You’re not asking to be left alone—you’re asking to be trusted.

question_text: What do you think is weighing on them lately?
option_text: D. They talk a lot about sacrifice—and want me to make it all worth it.
response_message: D. When your future feels tied to their past, it’s a heavy kind of love.
companion_advice:
They’ve worked hard—and maybe struggled—to give you this chance. That matters. So does your right to grow in your own way.
Try saying: “I see how much you’ve done for me. I want to make you proud—but I need space to find my own way.”

question_text: What do you think is weighing on them lately?
option_text: E. They care a lot about status—grades, school names, what other people think.
response_message: E. In some families, success isn’t just about effort—it’s about appearances.
companion_advice:
Try saying: “I know you want the best for me. But there are many ways to be successful—not all of them are what you think.”
That’s not rebellion—it’s honesty.

question_text: What do you think is weighing on them lately?
option_text: Other

question_text:
Even if it’s not your fight, it affects you. Some teens hide. Some freeze. Some jump in.

What’s your instinct when the room goes tense?
option_text: A. Go to my room and try to block it out.
response_message: A. You try to disappear. That fear sticks with you longer than anyone knows.
companion_advice: Blocking it out is protection—but your nervous system still hears it. Try calming yourself on purpose after: deep breaths, music, something grounding.

question_text: What’s your instinct when the room goes tense?
option_text: B. Stay calm and wait to check in afterward.
response_message: B. You stay calm and check in later. You’re more emotionally wise than most adults.
companion_advice: That’s emotional maturity. Try asking: ‘Do you want to talk about what happened?’ Even if they say no, you gave them an opening—and that matters.

question_text: What’s your instinct when the room goes tense?
option_text: C. Yell at them to shut up. That’s how they treat me and my siblings.
response_message: C. You yell back because that’s how things work in your house. Chaos teaches chaos—and sometimes it feels like the only way to be heard.
companion_advice:
You’re not wrong for reacting—but everyone deserves a peaceful home.
If it ever feels safe in the moment, try saying something like:
“Let's all talk calmly, starting now please.”
It might not fix everything—but it shows strength without adding to the fire.

question_text: What’s your instinct when the room goes tense?
option_text: Other

question_text:
The kitchen CEO has the power: they choose the menu, set the vibe, control the spice level, and who complains about it..
Curious how your setup compares to others? You’re about to help build the stats.

Who cooks in your home most of the time?
option_text: A. Mom
response_message: A. Classic. Moms keep the world running.
companion_advice: If Mom’s always in charge of meals, ask yourself: what would help her feel appreciated? A thank-you, a plate cleared, or even just saying, “That was good.”

question_text: Who cooks in your home most of the time?
option_text: B. Dad
response_message: B. Chef Dad in the kitchen!
companion_advice: If Dad cooks, that’s its own kind of care. Ask him about one of his go-to recipes—connection starts in weird places, even over garlic.

question_text: Who cooks in your home most of the time?
option_text: C. Sibling
response_message: C. Younger or older? Either way, impressive!
companion_advice: If your sibling’s in the kitchen, it might say a lot about your family roles. Try offering to help or swap a task—even if it’s small.

question_text: Who cooks in your home most of the time?
option_text: D. Me
response_message: D. Respect. Culinary skills = survival skills.
companion_advice: Cooking takes energy and planning. It s the best training for adulthood. Try choosing one night a week to cook just for you. What would you make, if no one else had a say?

question_text: Who cooks in your home most of the time?
option_text: E. Carryout / Delivery
response_message: E. The real MVP: takeout menus.
companion_advice: If takeout’s the norm, meals can still feel meaningful. Try setting the table differently or asking a question while you eat. Ritual matters more than the food.

question_text: Who cooks in your home most of the time?
option_text: Other

question_text: How’s the mess level in your house vs your room?
option_text: A. Our house is clean, but my room’s a mess
response_message: A. Your room might be your chaos zone—and that’s okay.
companion_advice: Try noticing what kind of mess feels comforting vs what drains you. That’s how you learn your own rhythm.

question_text: How’s the mess level in your house?
option_text: B. My room is clean, but the rest of the house is a mess
response_message: B. Your space is your peace—and you’ve claimed it. That’s a kind of self-care.
companion_advice: Try noticing what makes it feel good to you—so you can protect that feeling even when life gets messy.

question_text: How’s the mess level in your house?
option_text: C. About the same—messy or clean
response_message: Your space matches your environment. That can mean comfort… or stuckness.
companion_advice: Try asking: is this working for me, or do I want something different?

question_text: How’s the mess level in your house?

question_text:
Some chores you’re asked to do. Others just… become yours.
Cooking, cleaning, babysitting—every home runs on someone’s effort.

Which jobs do you find yourself doing (even when no one says thanks)?
option_text: A. Cleaning
response_message: A. You keep things together. That’s power.
companion_advice: You bring order to the chaos. That’s a quiet kind of leadership. Hope you—and your family—take time to notice and enjoy the calm you create.

question_text: Which jobs do you find yourself doing (even when no one says thanks)?
option_text: B. Cooking
response_message: B. Your meals might be your love language.
companion_advice: Cooking is power, creativity, design—and a lifelong skill. Hope you enjoy it on your terms. And yeah, fingers crossed someone else does the dishes.

question_text: Which jobs do you find yourself doing (even when no one says thanks)?
option_text: C. Taking care of younger siblings
response_message: C. You’re like a second parent. That’s a lot.
companion_advice: You’re exercising leadership—and being a role model, whether they say it or not. Just make sure you get space to be a kid too. That balance matters.

question_text: Which jobs do you find yourself doing (even when no one says thanks)?

question_text:
Some people get paid for chores. Some get paid for grades. Some get… nothing.
Allowance rules say a lot about how families see effort, trust, and money.
Curious how your setup compares to others? You’re about to help build the stats.

Is your allowance based on anything?
option_text: A. Housework
response_message: A. Work hard, earn cash. Feels like a mini job.
companion_advice: Getting paid for chores teaches a lot—but your value isn’t just in what you get paid. Try noticing the difference your effort makes—at home, and in who you’re becoming. Payment is nice, but contribution runs deeper.

question_text: Is your allowance based on anything?
option_text: B. School performance
response_message: B. Grades for money... sounds like pressure with a paycheck.
companion_advice: Getting paid for grades sounds simple—but it can mess with your head. Try separating effort from outcome. Ask yourself: “Did I try today? What did I learn?” That mindset lasts longer than any reward.

question_text: Is your allowance based on anything?
option_text: C. Unconditional
response_message: C. Trust without terms. That’s rare.
companion_advice: Being trusted without conditions is rare. If that’s your situation, ask yourself: “How can I keep that trust strong?” Respect goes both ways.

What do you usually do with your allowance?

response_message: A. A quiet flex. You’re thinking ahead.
companion_advice: Saving shows vision. But don’t forget to enjoy now too. Try setting aside a tiny bit just for fun—it helps the future-you and the current-you get along.

question_text: What do you usually do with your allowance?
option_text: B. Buy birthday or Christmas gifts
response_message: B. Giving feels better when it’s from your own stash.
companion_advice: Giving from your own pocket is powerful. Try writing one line about why a gift mattered to you—that memory will last longer than the receipt.

question_text: What do you usually do with your allowance?

response_message: C. Joy is a smart investment too.

You don’t always say it out loud—but it still leaks out. Some teens hide. Some shut down. Some start fights.

When something hurts, what do you actually do at home?
option_text: A. I hide in my room and wait for it to pass.
response_message: A. You hide away and wait it out. Just don’t forget—you’re not meant to carry this alone.
companion_advice: Crying in secret helps you release what words can’t. But your sadness still deserves a witness—even if it’s a journal, a song, or a safe person.

question_text: When something hurts, what do you actually do at home?
option_text: B. I talk to someone in my family who usually understands.
response_message: B. Not everyone has that. You do—and you reach for it when it counts. That’s a gift.
companion_advice: Since talking helps, ask yourself this: What makes that person easy to open up to? That answer is gold—for other relationships too.

question_text: When something hurts, what do you actually do at home?
option_text: C. I get mad at everyone.  It just spills out.
response_message: C. It spills out as anger. That doesn’t make you a bad person—it means something’s hurting.
companion_advice: If sadness starts fights, try this line: 'I’m upset, but I don’t want to argue.' It can change the entire direction of the room.

companion_advice: You shouldn’t have to break down to be believed. Help should come before the fall.

companion_advice: Please don’t skip straight to advice. Listen first. That’s what lands. I’d like it if you asked how I’m feeling, not just how school or stuff is going.

What would actually help you feel seen and heard?

What do you wish your parents did differently to support you?
option_text: A. Listen without interrupting or trying to fix it.
response_message: A. You don’t want to ask—and you still wish they noticed.
companion_advice: Try this: the next time they lecture you, say something calmly, like “Can I just talk for a few minutes without advice? I’m not asking you to fix it.” Even if they don't get it, you planted the seed. Then do something grounding for yourself after—like writing down what you wish they’d said. That gives your voice a place to land, even if it’s not with them (yet).

question_text: What do you wish your parents did differently to support you?
option_text: B. Trust that I’m trying—even if I don’t do things their way.
response_message: B. You’re trying. It may not look familiar to them, but it matters to you—and that should count.
companion_advice: Try writing down what you are proud of lately—even if they don’t notice it yet. Try to say something capmly like “Even if it doesn’t look like it, I’m trying. I’d like some trust, even if you don’t totally get it.”

question_text: What do you wish your parents did differently to support you?
option_text: C. Stop comparing me to other kids or my siblings.
response_message: C. Comparing doesn’t push you forward—it pushes you away. You just want to be seen for who you are.
companion_advice: You deserve to be seen for your own story. Try telling someone, “That felt like a comparison—even if you didn’t mean it. Conparison makes me shut down. I want to be seen for who I am, not who I’m not."

option_text: B. I say I’m not sure, but I’m willing to learn.

question_text: If you give the wrong answer in class, what do you do next?

question_text: If you give the wrong answer in class, what do you do next?

companion_advice: Proving you're right might feel good—but proving you’re open-minded feels better. Ask: ‘What made me think that?’ That’s real learning.

question_text:
Teachers are asking for more meaningful teaching.
Students are asking for more purpose and connection.
And AI? It’s already answering the easy stuff—so what we teach (and how) has to evolve.
So what do you wish school did differently—to actually help students like you?
option_text: A. Teach us how to ask better questions—not just give right answers.
response_message: A. In the AI era, answers are easy. The skill is knowing what to ask next.
companion_advice:
Good questions unlock new ideas, deeper thinking, and real conversations. 
Try this: Before asking “What’s the answer?”—ask “What’s this really about?”

question_text: So what do you wish school did differently—to actually help students like you?
option_text: B. Show us why this matters—connect it to our futures.
response_message: B. Relevance builds motivation. Even boring topics have a spark inside them.
companion_advice:
Ask how this shows up in real life, in a job, in a problem we actually care about.
You’re not here to memorize. You’re here to build a map.

question_text: So what do you wish school did differently—to actually help students like you?
option_text: C. Let us try things. Create, fail, fix, repeat. That’s how we grow.
response_message: C. Trial and error isn’t slacking—it’s real learning in action.
companion_advice:
When we’re allowed to mess up and try again, we stop performing and start becoming.
Ask your teacher for a chance to show your learning your way—presentation, sketch, song, idea.

question_text: So what do you wish school did differently—to actually help students like you?
option_text: D. Treat school like a launchpad—not a sorting hat.
response_message: D. You’re not being graded on your worth—you’re being prepared to fly.
companion_advice:
Let teachers know you want to build skills, not just collect points.
This is where you test your wings, not prove you’re perfect.

question_text: So what do you wish school did differently—to actually help students like you?
option_text: E. Be human. Laugh, listen, show passion. We’ll mirror it.
response_message: E. Students don’t need flawless role models—we need real ones.
companion_advice:
When a teacher shares a story, a struggle, a weird fact they love? That’s the stuff we remember.
If a teacher inspired you this week—tell them. That spark deserves to travel back.
